[src:viewport-responsive/css-media] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:viewport-responsive/css-media] It’s been available across browsers since July 2015.
[src:viewport-responsive/css-media] The **`@media`** CSS at-rule can be used to apply part of a style sheet based on the result of one or more media queries.
[src:viewport-responsive/css-media] With it, you specify a media query and a block of CSS to apply to the document if and only if the media query matches the device on which the content is being used.
[src:viewport-responsive/css-media] The `@media` at-rule may be placed at the top level of your code or nested inside any other conditional group at-rule.
[src:viewport-responsive/css-media] For a discussion of media query syntax, please see Using media queries.
[src:viewport-responsive/css-media] A media query's `<media-query-list>` includes `<media-type>`s, `<media-feature>s`, and logical operators.
[src:viewport-responsive/css-media] A *`<media-type>`* describes the general category of a device.
[src:viewport-responsive/css-media] Except when using the `only` logical operator, the media type is optional and the `all` type is implied.
[src:viewport-responsive/css-media] Intended for paged material and documents viewed on a screen in print preview mode.
[src:viewport-responsive/css-media] A *`<media feature>`* describes specific characteristics of the user agent, output device, or environment.
[src:viewport-responsive/css-media] Media feature expressions test for their presence, value, or range of values, and are entirely optional.
[src:viewport-responsive/css-media] Each media feature expression must be surrounded by parentheses.
[src:viewport-responsive/css-media] Does any available input mechanism allow the user to hover over elements?
