[src:viewport-responsive/css-media] Detects if the user has requested the system increase or decrease the amount of contrast between adjacent colors.
[src:viewport-responsive/css-media] Detects if the user has requested the web content that consumes less internet traffic.
[src:viewport-responsive/css-media] The user prefers less motion on the page.
[src:viewport-responsive/css-media] Detects if a user has enabled a setting on their device to reduce the transparent or translucent layer effects used on the device.
[src:viewport-responsive/css-media] Whether display output is progressive or interlaced.
[src:viewport-responsive/css-media] Detects whether scripting (i.e., JavaScript) is available.
[src:viewport-responsive/css-media] Detects the shape of the device to distinguish rectangular and round displays.
[src:viewport-responsive/css-media] How frequently the output device can modify the appearance of content.
[src:viewport-responsive/css-media] Detects whether the device has a specified number of viewport segments laid out vertically.
[src:viewport-responsive/css-media] Combination of brightness, contrast ratio, and color depth that are supported by the video plane of user agent and the output device.
[src:viewport-responsive/css-media] Width of the viewport including width of scrollbar.
[src:viewport-responsive/css-media] The number of device pixels per CSS pixel.
[src:viewport-responsive/css-media] Use the `resolution` feature with the `dppx` unit instead.
[src:viewport-responsive/css-media] The browser supports `-webkit` prefixed CSS `animation`.
[src:viewport-responsive/css-media] Use the `@supports (animation)` feature query instead.
[src:viewport-responsive/css-media] The browser supports `-webkit` prefixed 2D CSS `transform`.
[src:viewport-responsive/css-media] Use the `@supports (transform)` feature query instead.
[src:viewport-responsive/css-media] The browser supports `-webkit` prefixed 3D CSS `transform`.
[src:viewport-responsive/css-media] The browser supports `-webkit` prefixed CSS `transition`.
[src:viewport-responsive/css-media] Use the `@supports (transition)` feature query instead.
[src:viewport-responsive/css-media] The *logical operators* `not`, `and`, `only`, and `or` can be used to compose a complex media query.
[src:viewport-responsive/css-media] You can also combine multiple media queries into a single rule by separating them with commas.
[src:viewport-responsive/css-media] Used for combining multiple media features together into a single media query, requiring each chained feature to return `true` for the query to be `true`.
[src:viewport-responsive/css-media] It is also used for joining media features with media types.
[src:viewport-responsive/css-media] Used to negate a media query, returning `true` if the query would otherwise return `false`.
[src:viewport-responsive/css-media] If present in a comma-separated list of queries, it will only negate the specific query to which it is applied.
[src:viewport-responsive/css-media] Applies a style only if an entire query matches.
[src:viewport-responsive/css-media] It is useful for preventing older browsers from applying selected styles.
[src:viewport-responsive/css-media] When not using `only`, older browsers would interpret the query `screen and (width <= 500px)` as `screen`, ignoring the remainder of the query, and applying its styles on all screens.
[src:viewport-responsive/css-media] If you use the `only` operator, you *must also* specify a media type.
[src:viewport-responsive/css-media] Commas are used to combine multiple media queries into a single rule.
[src:viewport-responsive/css-media] Each query in a comma-separated list is treated separately from the others.
[src:viewport-responsive/css-media] Thus, if any of the queries in a list is `true`, the entire media statement returns `true`.
[src:viewport-responsive/css-media] In other words, lists behave like a logical `or` operator.
[src:viewport-responsive/css-media] Some media queries have corresponding user agent client hints.
[src:viewport-responsive/css-media] These are HTTP headers that request content that is pre-optimized for the particular media requirement.
[src:viewport-responsive/css-media] They include `Sec-CH-Prefers-Color-Scheme` and `Sec-CH-Prefers-Reduced-Motion`.
[src:viewport-responsive/css-media] To best accommodate people who adjust a site's text size, use `em`s when you need a `<length>` for your media queries.
[src:viewport-responsive/css-media] Both `em` and `px` are valid units, but `em` works better if the user changes the browser text size.
[src:viewport-responsive/css-media] Also consider media queries or HTTP user agent client hints to improve the user's experience.
[src:viewport-responsive/css-media] For example, the media query `prefers-reduced-motion` or the equivalent HTTP header `Sec-CH-Prefers-Reduced-Motion`) can be used to minimize the amount of animation or motion used based on user preferences.
[src:viewport-responsive/css-media] Because of this potential, a browser may opt to fudge the returned values in some manner in order to prevent them from being used to precisely identify a computer.
[src:viewport-responsive/css-media] A browser might also offer additional measures in this area; for example, if Firefox's "Resist Fingerprinting" setting is enabled, many media queries report default values rather than values representing the actual device state.
[src:viewport-responsive/css-media] For more examples, please see Using media queries.
[src:viewport-responsive/responsive-web-design] , on a computer screen (left) and on a mobile phone screen (right).
[src:viewport-responsive/responsive-web-design] The elements rearrange themselves into a more mobile friendly layout.
[src:viewport-responsive/responsive-web-design] Responsive web design became more important as users of mobile devices came to account for the majority of website visitors.
[src:viewport-responsive/responsive-web-design] In 2015, for instance, Google announced Mobilegeddon and started to boost the page ranking of mobile-friendly sites when searching from a mobile device.
[src:viewport-responsive/responsive-web-design] Responsive web design is an example of user interface plasticity.
[src:viewport-responsive/responsive-web-design] Luke Wroblewski has summarized some of the responsive and mobile design challenges and created a catalog of multi-device layout patterns.
[src:viewport-responsive/responsive-web-design] He suggested that, compared with a simple responsive web design approach, device experience or RESS (responsive web design with server-side components) approaches can provide a user experience that is better optimized for mobile devices.
[src:viewport-responsive/responsive-web-design] Server-side CSS generator implementation of stylesheet languages like Sass can be part of such an approach.
[src:viewport-responsive/responsive-web-design] Google has recommended responsive design for smartphone websites over other approaches.
[src:viewport-responsive/responsive-web-design] Although many publishers have implemented responsive designs, one challenge for responsive design adoption was that some banner advertisements and videos were not fluid.
[src:viewport-responsive/responsive-web-design] However, search advertising and (banner) display advertising came to support specific device platform targeting and different advertisement size formats for desktop, smartphone, and basic mobile devices.
[src:viewport-responsive/responsive-web-design] Different landing page URLs have been used for different platforms, or Ajax has been used to display different advertisement variants on a page.
[src:viewport-responsive/responsive-web-design] CSS tables permitted hybrid fixed and fluid layouts.
[src:viewport-responsive/responsive-web-design] There have been many ways of validating and testing responsive web designs, ranging from mobile site validators and mobile emulators to simultaneous testing tools like Adobe Edge Inspect.
[src:viewport-responsive/responsive-web-design] The Chrome, Firefox and Safari browsers and developer tools have offered responsive design viewport resizing tools, as do third parties.
[src:viewport-responsive/responsive-web-design] The W3C specification of HTML+ stated that websites have to be rendered according to the user preferences.
[src:viewport-responsive/responsive-web-design] The customization of web page layout was lacking however.
[src:viewport-responsive/responsive-web-design] Many web developers resorted to ordinary HTML tables as a way to customize the layout and bring some basic responsiveness to their websites at the same time.
[src:viewport-responsive/responsive-web-design] Limited browser capabilities meant that for Internet Explorer, the layout could adapt dynamically in the browser whereas, for Netscape, the page had to be reloaded from the server when resized.
[src:viewport-responsive/responsive-web-design] Cameron Adams created a demonstration in 2004.
[src:viewport-responsive/responsive-web-design] By 2008, a number of related terms such as "flexible", "liquid", "fluid", and "elastic" were being used to describe layouts.
[src:viewport-responsive/responsive-web-design] CSS3 media queries were almost ready for prime time in late 2008/early 2009.
[src:viewport-responsive/responsive-web-design] Ethan Marcotte coined the term *responsive web design*—and defined it to mean fluid grid / flexible images / media queries—in a May 2010 article in *A List Apart*.
[src:viewport-responsive/responsive-web-design] He described the theory and practice of responsive web design in his brief 2011 book titled *Responsive Web Design*.
[src:viewport-responsive/responsive-web-design] Responsive design was listed as #2 in Top Web Design Trends for 2012 by .net magazine after progressive enhancement at #1.
[src:viewport-responsive/responsive-web-design] Mashable called 2013 the Year of Responsive Web Design.
[src:viewport-responsive/responsive-web-design] User interface plasticity is the capacity of a user interface to withstand variations of both the system's physical characteristics and the environment while preserving usability.
[src:viewport-responsive/using-media-queries] A media query is composed of an optional *media type* and any number of *media feature* expressions, which may optionally be combined in various ways using *logical operators*.
[src:viewport-responsive/using-media-queries] A media query computes to `true` when the media type (if specified) matches the device on which a document is being displayed *and* all media feature expressions compute as true.
[src:viewport-responsive/using-media-queries] Queries involving unknown media types are always false.
[src:viewport-responsive/using-media-queries] Media types describe the general category of a given device.
[src:viewport-responsive/using-media-queries] Although websites are commonly designed with screens in mind, you may want to create styles that target special devices such as printers or audio-based screen readers.
[src:viewport-responsive/using-media-queries] See media types for the list of available media types.
[src:viewport-responsive/using-media-queries] Because media types describe devices in very broad terms, most of the originally-defined media types were deprecated, with just `screen`, `print`, and `all` remaining.
[src:viewport-responsive/using-media-queries] To target more specific attributes, use *media features* instead.
[src:viewport-responsive/using-media-queries] Media features describe the specific characteristics of a given user agent, output device, or environment.
[src:viewport-responsive/using-media-queries] For instance, you can apply specific styles to widescreen monitors, computers that use mice, or devices that are being used in low-light conditions.
[src:viewport-responsive/using-media-queries] Media features are either range or discrete.
[src:viewport-responsive/using-media-queries] Many *range features* can be prefixed with "min-" or "max-" to express "minimum condition" or "maximum condition" constraints.
[src:viewport-responsive/using-media-queries] With media query range features, you can either use the inclusive `min-` and `max-` prefixes or the more concise range syntax operators `<=` and `>=`.
[src:viewport-responsive/using-media-queries] The range comparisons above are inclusive.
[src:viewport-responsive/using-media-queries] To exclude the comparison value, use `<` and/or `>`.
[src:viewport-responsive/using-media-queries] If you create a media feature query without specifying a value, the nested styles will be used as long as the feature's value is not `0` or `none`.
[src:viewport-responsive/using-media-queries] If a feature doesn't apply to the device on which the browser is running, expressions involving that media feature are always false.
[src:viewport-responsive/using-media-queries] For more Media feature examples, please see the reference page for each specific feature.
[src:viewport-responsive/using-media-queries] Sometimes you may want to create a media query that depends on multiple conditions.
[src:viewport-responsive/using-media-queries] This is where the *logical operators* come in: `not`, `and`, and `only`.
[src:viewport-responsive/using-media-queries] In the previous example, we saw the `and` operator used to group a media *type* with a media *feature*.
[src:viewport-responsive/using-media-queries] The `and` operator can also combine multiple media features within a single media query.
[src:viewport-responsive/using-media-queries] The `not` operator negates a media query, or a media feature when used with brackets, basically reversing their normal meanings.
[src:viewport-responsive/using-media-queries] The `or` operator can, under certain conditions, be used to combine multiple media features within a single media query.
[src:viewport-responsive/using-media-queries] Lastly, the `only` operator was used to prevent older browsers from applying the styles without evaluating the media feature expressions but it has no effect in modern browsers.
[src:viewport-responsive/using-media-queries] The `and` keyword combines a media feature with a media type *or* other media features.
[src:viewport-responsive/using-media-queries] You can use a comma-separated list of media queries to apply styles when the user's device matches any one of various media types, features, or states.
[src:viewport-responsive/using-media-queries] The following rule contains two media queries.
[src:viewport-responsive/using-media-queries] In this example, if the user is printing to a PDF and the page height is 800px, the media query returns true because the first query component — which tests whether the viewport has a height of `680px` or more — is true.
[src:viewport-responsive/using-media-queries] Likewise, if a user is on a smartphone in portrait mode with a viewport height of 480px, the media query returns true because the second query component is true.
[src:viewport-responsive/using-media-queries] In a comma-separated list of media queries, the individual media queries end at the comma or, in the case of the last media query in the list, at the opening bracket (`{`).
[src:viewport-responsive/using-media-queries] The `not` keyword inverts the meaning of a single media query.
[src:viewport-responsive/using-media-queries] The `not` negates only the media query it is applied to.
[src:viewport-responsive/using-media-queries] The `not`, without parenthesis, negates all the features within the media query in which it is contained.
[src:viewport-responsive/using-media-queries] This means, in a comma-separated list of media queries, each `not` applies to the single query it is contained within, applying to *all* the features within that single query.
[src:viewport-responsive/using-media-queries] Because the query starts with a media type `screen`, you *cannot* wrap `screen and (color)` with parentheses.
[src:viewport-responsive/using-media-queries] Parentheses limit the components of the query that get negated.
[src:viewport-responsive/using-media-queries] `not` only negates the query to its right.
[src:viewport-responsive/using-media-queries] The `not (hover)` matches if the device has no hover capability.
[src:viewport-responsive/using-media-queries] In this case, because of its ordering, the `not` applies to `hover` but not to `screen`.
[src:viewport-responsive/using-media-queries] The `only` keyword prevents older browsers that do not support media queries with media features from applying the given styles.
[src:viewport-responsive/using-media-queries] You can use `or` to test for a match among more than one feature, resolving to `true` if any of the features are true.
[src:viewport-responsive/using-media-queries] Note that you cannot use the `or` operator on the same level as the `and` and `not` operators.
[src:viewport-responsive/using-media-queries] You can either separate the media features with a comma or use parenthesis to group sub-expressions of media features to clarify the order of evaluation.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] This article explains the concept of the viewport — what it is and its impact in terms of CSS, SVG, and mobile devices.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] This article defines the initial viewport and actual viewport, and differentiates between the visual viewport and the layout viewport.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] A **viewport** is a user agent feature used to establish the initial containing block for continuous media.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] The generic *viewport* term generally refers to the area in computer graphics being currently viewed.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] In web browser terms, that is generally the same as the browser window, excluding the UI, menu bar, etc.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] That is the part of the document you are viewing.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] The *initial viewport* refers to the window or viewing area of the UA before user agent styles, HTML `<meta>` tags, or CSS styles have overridden its size.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] The initial viewport size is based on the size of the window or viewing area, and not the content.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] The size of a full-screen user agent's initial viewport will differ between orientations and devices, but will always be the same for the same device in the same orientation.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] The *actual viewport* is the viewport you get after processing the viewport `<meta>` tag.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] Content designed for large viewports may exhibit a variety of bugs when viewed in smaller viewports, including unintended wrapping, clipped content, and incorrectly sized scroll containers.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] The viewport meta tag provides hints about the initial size of the viewport.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] The actual viewport is the size defined by its `content` attribute.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] If this tag is omitted, some mobile browsers render content using a fixed initial containing block width, typically `980px`.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] They set the width of the actual viewport to this value, then scale the content down to fit it, making the CSS pixel size smaller than an actual pixel.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] Documents, like this article, may be very long.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] Your viewport is everything that is currently visible; notably, the "what is a viewport" section, and perhaps some of the navigation menu.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] The size of the viewport depends on the size of the screen, whether the browser is in fullscreen mode or not, and whether or not the browser is zoomed in.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] Content outside the viewport, such as the *See Also* section in this document, is likely to not be visible onscreen until scrolled into view.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] For paged media, the initial containing block is based on the page area.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] The page area can be set through `@page` rules.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] To recap, the viewport is basically the part of the document that is currently visible.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] The width of the viewport is not always the width of the window.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] In an experiment with these, the `innerWidth` and `outerWidth` was seen to be the same, but the `outerHeight` was 100px taller than the `innerHeight`.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] This is because the `outerHeight` includes the browser chrome: measurements were taken on a browser with an address bar and bookmarks bar totalling 100px in height, but no chrome on the left or right of the window.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] The area within the `innerHeight` and `innerWidth` is generally considered the **layout viewport**.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] The browser chrome is not considered part of the viewport.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] When zoomed in, both Firefox and Chrome report the new CSS pixel size for `innerWidth` and `clientWidth`.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] The values returned for the `outerWidth` and `outerHeight` depend on the browser: Firefox reports the new value in CSS pixels, but Chrome returns the length in the default pixel size.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] The viewport was originally 1200 x 800 pixels.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] Upon zooming in, the viewport became 800 x 533 pixels.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] Sticky headers or footers, with the following styles, will stick to the top and bottom of the *layout viewport* respectively.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] We got the 800 x 533 measurement when we zoomed in using the keyboard.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] The header and footer stayed flush against the top and bottom of the window.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] But what if we had pinched-zoomed on a tablet?
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] What if a dynamic keyboard pops open on a phone?
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] The web contains two viewports, the **layout viewport** and the **visual viewport**.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] The visual viewport is the part of the web page that is currently visible in the browser and can change.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] When the user pinch-zooms the page, pops open a dynamic keyboard, or when a previously hidden address bar becomes visible, the visual viewport shrinks but the layout viewport is unchanged.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] Fixed sticky headers or footers, as discussed above, stick to the top and bottom of the *layout viewport*, and therefore remain in view when we zoom in with the keyboard.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] If you pinch-zoom, the layout viewport may not be fully visible.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] If you magnify from the middle of the layout viewport, the content will expand in all four directions.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] If you have a sticky header or footer, they will still be stuck to the top or bottom of the layout viewport, but they may not be visible at the top and bottom of the device's screen — which is the visual viewport.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] The visual viewport is the currently visible portion of the layout viewport.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] If you scroll down, you are changing the contents of the visual viewport and bringing the bottom of the layout viewport into view, displaying the sticky footer, which will then stay stuck at the bottom.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] The visual viewport is the visual portion of a screen not including on-screen keyboards, areas outside of a pinch-zoom area, or other feature that doesn't scale with the dimensions of a page.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] The visual viewport is the same size as the layout viewport or smaller.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] For a page containing iframes, objects, or external SVG, both the containing pages and each included file has their own unique window object.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] Only the top-level window has a visual viewport that may be distinct from the layout viewport.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] For included documents, the visual viewport and layout viewport are the same.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] The layout viewport and visual viewport described above are not the only viewports you will encounter.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] Any sub-viewport that is fully or partially displayed within the layout viewport is considered a visual viewport.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] We generally think of `width` and `height` media queries as being relative to the width and height of the browser window.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] They are actually relative to the viewport, which is the window in the main document but is the intrinsic size of the element's parent in a nested browsing context like objects, iframes and SVG.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] In CSS, we also have length units based on the viewport size.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] A `vh` unit is 1% of the layout viewport's height.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] Similarly, the `vw` unit is 1% of the layout viewport's width.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] Inside an `<iframe>`, the visual viewport is the size of the inner width and height of the iframe, rather than the parent document.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] You can set any height and width on an iframe, but the whole document may not be visible.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] If you use viewport length units in your CSS within the iframe document, `1vh` will be 1% of the height of the iframe, and `1vw` will be 1% of the width of the document.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] If the iframe is set to 50vw, it will be 50% of the width of the `1200px` parent document in our example above, or `600px`, with `1vw` being `6px`.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] When zoomed in, the iframe shrinks to `400px` and `1vw` becomes `4px`.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] A width-based media query within the iframe document is relative to the iframe's viewport.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] If the above CSS is included in the iframe, the paragraphs will become red when the user has zoomed in, but this style does not apply in the non-zoomed-in state.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] In an SVG document, the viewport is the visible area of the SVG image.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] You can set any height and width on an `<svg>`, but the whole image might not be visible.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] The area that is visible is called the viewport.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] The size of the viewport can be defined using the width and height attributes of the `<svg>` element.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] In this example, the viewport has an aspect ratio of 3:4 and is, by default, 400 by 300 units, with a unit generally being a CSS pixel.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] SVG also has an internal coordinate system defined via the viewBox attribute, which is not related to this viewport discussion.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] If you include an SVG file in your HTML, the viewport of the SVG is the initial containing block, or the width and height of the SVG container.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] Using the `@media` query in your SVG's CSS is relative to that container, not the browser.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] Generally, when you write the above media query, the styles are applied if the viewport, generally the browser window, is between 400px and 500px, inclusive.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] The width media query in the SVG is based on the element in which the SVG is contained — the `<img>` if the source is an SVG file, the SVG itself if the SVG is included directly into the HTML, or the parent if the parent element has a width assigned and — not the viewport's width.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] With the above media query being in our SVG file, the CSS is applied if the SVG container is between 400px and 500px.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] The `VisualViewport` interface provides a mechanism for querying and modifying the properties of the visual viewport.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] The `Viewport` interface provides a mechanism for querying and modifying the properties of the visual viewport.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] Mobile devices come in all shapes and sizes, with screens of differing device pixel ratios.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] The mobile browser's viewport is the area of the window in which web content can be seen, which is not necessarily the same size as the rendered page.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] Mobile browsers render pages in a virtual window or viewport, generally at 980px, which is usually wider than the screen, and then shrink the rendered result down so it can all be seen at once.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] Users can then pan and zoom to see different areas of the page.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] For example, if a mobile screen has a width of 320px, a website might be rendered with a virtual viewport of 980px, and then it will be shrunk down to fit into the 320px space, which, depending on the design, is illegible for many if not everyone.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] The `width` property controls the size of the viewport.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] It should preferably be set to `device-width`, which is the width of the screen in CSS pixels at a scale of 100%.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-concepts] There are other properties, including `maximum-scale`, `minimum-scale`, and `user-scalable`, which control whether users can zoom the page in or out, but the default values are the best for accessibility and user experience, so these can be omitted.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-meta-element] The **`viewport`** value for the `name` attribute of a `<meta>` element gives hints about how the viewport should be sized.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-meta-element] If specified, you define viewport-related behaviors using a `content` attribute in the `<meta>` element as a comma-separated list of one or more values.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-meta-element] The `content` attribute must be defined, and its value sets various viewport-related behaviors.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-meta-element] Its value is a comma-separated list of one or more key-value pairs specified as `key=value`.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-meta-element] Controls the (minimum) pixel width of the viewport (see viewport width and screen width).
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-meta-element] It can be set to a positive whole number of pixels between 1 and 10000 (like `width=600`) or to the special value `device-width`, which is the physical size of the device screen in CSS pixels.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-meta-element] This value establishes the value of the `vw` unit.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-meta-element] Controls the (minimum) pixel height of the viewport (see viewport width and screen width).
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-meta-element] It can be set to a positive whole number of pixels between 1 and 10000 (like `height=400`) or to the special value `device-height`, which is the physical size of the device screen in CSS pixels.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-meta-element] This value establishes the value of the `vh` unit.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-meta-element] Defines the ratio between the device width (`device-width` in portrait mode or `device-height` in landscape mode) and the viewport size.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-meta-element] It can be a number between `0.0` and `10.0`.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-meta-element] It must be greater or equal to the `minimum-scale` or the behavior is undefined.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-meta-element] Browser settings can ignore this rule, and iOS10+ ignores it by default.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-meta-element] It must be smaller or equal to the `maximum-scale` or the behavior is undefined.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-meta-element] A boolean indicating if the user can zoom the web page.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-meta-element] It can be either `yes` or `no`, defaulting to `yes`.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-meta-element] Specifies the effect that interactive UI widgets, such as virtual keyboards, have on a page's viewport.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-meta-element] It can be the keyword `resizes-visual`, `resizes-content`, or `overlays-content`.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-meta-element] When the viewport gets resized, the initial containing block also gets resized, thereby affecting the computed size of viewport units.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-meta-element] Defines the viewable portions of the web page.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-meta-element] It can be one of the keywords `auto`, `contain`, or `cover`.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-meta-element] The browser's viewport is the area of the window in which web content can be seen.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-meta-element] Some mobile devices and other narrow screens render pages in a virtual window or viewport that is wider than the screen, and then shrink the rendered result down to fit the screen size.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-meta-element] Users can then zoom and pan to look more closely at different areas of the page.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-meta-element] For example, if a mobile screen has a width of 640px, pages might be rendered with a virtual viewport of 980px, and then it will be shrunk down to fit into the 640px space.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-meta-element] This is done because not all pages are optimized for mobile and break (or at least look bad) when rendered at a small viewport width.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-meta-element] This virtual viewport is a way to make non-mobile-optimized sites in general look better on narrow screen devices.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-meta-element] However, this mechanism is not so good for pages that are optimized for narrow screens using media queries — if the virtual viewport is 980px for example, media queries that kick in at 640px or 480px or less will never be used, limiting the effectiveness of such responsive design techniques.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-meta-element] The viewport `<meta>` element mitigates this problem of virtual viewport on narrow screen devices.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-meta-element] Sites can set their viewport to a specific size.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-meta-element] For example, the definition `"width=320, initial-scale=1"` can be used to fit precisely onto a small phone display in portrait mode.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-meta-element] This can cause problems when the browser renders a page at a larger size.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-meta-element] To fix this, browsers will expand the viewport width if necessary to fill the screen at the requested scale.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-meta-element] This is especially useful on large-screen devices.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-meta-element] For pages that set an initial or maximum scale, this means the `width` property actually translates into a *minimum* viewport width.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-meta-element] For example, if your layout needs at least 500 pixels of width then you can use the following markup.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-meta-element] Screen resolutions have risen to the size that individual pixels are indistinguishable by the human eye.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-meta-element] For example, smartphones often have small screens with resolutions upwards of 1920–1080 pixels (≈400dpi).
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-meta-element] Because of this, many browsers can display their pages in a smaller physical size by translating multiple hardware pixels for each CSS "pixel".
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-meta-element] Initially, this caused usability and readability problems on many touch-optimized websites.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-meta-element] On high dpi screens, pages with `initial-scale=1` will effectively be zoomed by browsers.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-meta-element] Their text will be smooth and crisp, but their bitmap images may not take advantage of the full screen resolution.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-meta-element] To get sharper images on these screens, web developers may want to design images – or whole layouts – at a higher scale than their final size and then scale them down using CSS or viewport properties.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-meta-element] The default pixel ratio depends on the display density.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-meta-element] On a display with density less than 200dpi, the ratio is 1.0.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-meta-element] On displays with density between 200 and 300dpi, the ratio is 1.5.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-meta-element] For displays with density over 300dpi, the ratio is the integer floor (*density*/150dpi).
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-meta-element] Note that the default ratio is true only when the viewport scale equals 1.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-meta-element] Otherwise, the relationship between CSS pixels and device pixels depends on the current zoom level.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-meta-element] Interactive UI widgets of the browser can influence the size of the page's viewports.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-meta-element] The most common such UI widget is a virtual keyboard.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-meta-element] To control which resize behavior the browser should use, set the `interactive-widget` property.
[src:viewport-responsive/viewport-meta-element] By default, the virtual keyboard only resizes the visual viewport, which doesn't affect the layout of the page.
[src:viewport-responsive/window-matchmedia] The `Window` interface's **`matchMedia()`** method returns a new `MediaQueryList` object that can then be used to determine if the `document` matches the media query string, as well as to monitor the document to detect when it matches (or stops matching) that media query.
[src:viewport-responsive/window-matchmedia] A string specifying the media query to parse into a `MediaQueryList`.
[src:viewport-responsive/window-matchmedia] Just like in CSS, any media feature must be wrapped in parentheses inside the expression.
[src:viewport-responsive/window-matchmedia] For example: `matchMedia("(width <= 600px)")` or `matchMedia("(orientation: landscape)")` work, whereas `matchMedia("width < 600px")` or `matchMedia("orientation: landscape")` do not.
[src:viewport-responsive/window-matchmedia] Keywords for media types (`all`, `print`, `screen`) and logical operators (`and`, `or`, `not`, `only`) do not need to be wrapped in parentheses.
[src:viewport-responsive/window-matchmedia] A new `MediaQueryList` object for the media query.
[src:viewport-responsive/window-matchmedia] Use this object's properties and events to detect matches and to monitor for changes to those matches over time.
[src:viewport-responsive/window-matchmedia] You can use the returned media query to perform both instantaneous and event-driven checks to see if the document matches the media query.
[src:viewport-responsive/window-matchmedia] To perform a one-time, instantaneous check to see if the document matches the media query, look at the value of the `matches` property, which will be `true` if the document meets the media query's requirements.
[src:viewport-responsive/window-matchmedia] If you need to be kept aware of whether or not the document matches the media query at all times, you can instead watch for the `change` event to be delivered to the object.
[src:viewport-responsive/window-matchmedia] There's a good example of this in the article on `Window.devicePixelRatio`.
[src:viewport-responsive/window-matchmedia] This example runs the media query `(width <= 600px)` and displays the value of the resulting `MediaQueryList`'s `matches` property in a `<span>`; as a result, the output will say "true" if the viewport is less than or equal to 600 pixels wide, and will say "false" if the window is wider than that.
[src:viewport-responsive/window-matchmedia] The JavaScript code passes the media query to match into `matchMedia()` to compile it, then sets the `<span>`'s `innerText` to the value of the results' `matches` property, so that it indicates whether or not the document matches the media query at the moment the page was loaded.
[src:viewport-responsive/window-matchmedia] A simple `<span>` to receive the output.
[src:viewport-responsive/window-matchmedia] See Testing media queries programmatically for additional code examples.
